		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2013"></a><br><code>sle2013/paper02</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> paper:</span><br><i>Micro-Machinations: A DSL for Game Economies</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/PaulKlint.html">Paul Klint</a>, <a href="../profile/RiemervanRozen.html">Riemer van Rozen</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_3">10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_3</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The paper proposes a dedicated DSL to let game designers specify and communicate game-economy mechanics.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4e.html"><span class="tagL">T4E: Simulation</span></a><ul><li> The DSL targets the modeling and (typically) simulation/analysis of game economies to understand emergent behavior.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> A stated goal is improving designer productivity and designer–engineer communication, i.e., human-centered usability concerns.
</li></ul></li></ul>
